","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Carmine, Angelo, Carmel, Cosimo, Gaetano, Gasper, Nino, Pietro, Sal, Santino.","Italian (Sicily): habitational name from a place in Sicily calledCambria, probably of Arabic origin."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Adèle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adèle de Cambrai was born in 1010, her father, Gauthier d'Oisy de Cambrai II, was 38 and her mother, Ermentrude D'ARRAS d'Ostrevant, was 32. She married Hughes \"de Douai\" Fleming x before 1020, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"1010–":"1010–Surnud","1005–Female":"1005–Surnud","1010–Female":"1010–Surnud","1015–Male":"1015–Surnud","1035–1075":"1035–1075","1002–1048":"1002–1048","1037–1096":"1037–1096","1040–1140":"1040–1140","1045–1111":"1045–1111","0972–1041":"0972–1041","0978–1041":"0978–1041","1010":"1010","1075":"1075","1041":"1041","1140":"1140","1096":"1096","1040":"1040","0972":"0972","1005":"1005","1037":"1037","1048":"1048","1015":"1015","1002":"1002","1035":"1035","1045":"1045","1111":"1111","before 1020":"enne 1020","about 1037":"umbes 1037","0978":"0978","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Cambrai, Nord, Hauts-de-France, France":"Cambrai, Nord, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Europe":"Europe","Skipton In Topcliffe, Yorkshire, England":"Skipton in Topcliffe, Yorkshire, England","Namur, Belgique":"Namur, Belgia"},"fi":{"1010–":"1010–Kuollut","1005–Female":"1005–Kuollut","1010–Female":"1010–Kuollut","1015–Male":"1015–Kuollut","1035–1075":"1035–1075","1002–1048":"1002–1048","1037–1096":"1037–1096","1040–1140":"1040–1140","1045–1111":"1045–1111","0972–1041